  "prompt": "What are the strongest majors in terms of job prospects and what are the weakest majors at Central Washington University?",
  "response": "Central Washington University (CWU) offers a wide range of academic programs, and job prospects can vary significantly depending on the field of study. To determine the strongest and weakest majors in terms of job prospects at CWU, we can consider factors such as employment rates, industry demand, median salaries, and trends in job market growth. Here is a general overview based on common trends for universities, including CWU:\n\n### Strongest Majors in Terms of Job Prospects:\n\n1. **Computer Science and Information Technology:**\n   - High demand for tech professionals\n   - Strong job growth and high median salaries\n   - Opportunities in various industries including software development, cybersecurity, and data analysis\n\n2. **Nursing and Health Sciences:**\n   - Persistent shortage of healthcare professionals\n   - High job security and competitive salaries\n   - Diverse opportunities within clinical, research, and administrative roles\n\n3. **Engineering:**\n   - Consistent demand for engineers in various sectors such as civil, mechanical, electrical, and aerospace engineering\n   - Strong job market growth and lucrative salaries\n   - Opportunities for both public and private sector employment\n\n4. **Business Administration and Accounting:**\n   - Broad applicability in numerous industries\n   - Steady job growth in fields like finance, marketing, management, and entrepreneurship\n   - Competitive salaries and opportunities for career advancement\n\n5. **Education:**\n   - Continuous need for teachers and educational administrators\n   - Opportunities across all levels of education, including K-12 and higher education\n   - Reasonable job security, though salaries may vary\n\n### Weakest Majors in Terms of Job Prospects:\n\n1. **Fine Arts:**\n   - Lower demand in the job market\n   - Often project-based or freelance work with variable income levels\n   - Competitive industry with fewer full-time, stable positions\n\n2. **Philosophy:**\n   - Limited direct job opportunities tied to the major\n   - Often requires further education or specialization for career advancement\n   - Lower median salaries as compared to technical or professional degrees\n\n3. **Literature and Creative Writing:**\n   - Challenging job market with fewer full-time positions\n   - Potential reliance on freelance work, teaching, or secondary careers\n   - Variable income dependent on projects, publications, and contracts\n\n4. **Anthropology and Sociology:**\n   - Limited job opportunities directly related to the field\n   - May require advanced degrees for better employment prospects\n   - Lower median salaries and less growth compared to STEM fields\n\n5. **Environmental Studies:**\n   - Job prospects can be variable and often reliant on local/regional demand\n   - Growth may be slower in comparison to tech and healthcare sectors\n   - Opportunities often tied to government, non-profits, or interdisciplinary roles\n\nIt\u2019s important to consider personal interests, strengths, and long-term career goals when choosing a major. Additionally, factors like internships, networking, additional certifications, and graduate studies can significantly impact job prospects regardless of the chosen field of study. Be sure to consult CWU\u2019s career services, academic advisors, and industry reports for the most current and detailed information.",
